      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The argument from Italian government officials reportedly is that supercars are so rare and driven less regularly than those boxes on wheels people call automobiles that they hardly make an environmental impact. After all, Lamborghini and Ferrari sell a small fraction of the cars Toyota or Ford does.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "We like this idea and quite frankly don’t see why they can’t make supercars without cats and other emissions equipment. Since they’re so rare and awesome, they should be allowed to not follow anything the ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "EPA",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
